5 Jun 2015, 03:11
Oliver Ward
the other main theory for relationship breakdown is the reasons of breakdown by duck. This theory describes that there are three main reasons for breakdown which are seen to occur most frequency. The first is lack of skills. This is where one individual is not pleasing the other as they lack the social skills required to make them happy. This could be something such as keeping a conversation together, or not being affectionate enough to the other person. The second explanation is the lack of stimulation - the lack of stimulation is where the partner feels ‘bored’ in the relationship - he feels like the relationship isn't going anywhere, or they arent having fun - the most common reason for this is the lack of sex life. The final explanation is maintenance difficulties. This is where the couple face external pressures on the relationship - such as a disapproving family, or most notably long distance relationships - for this reason, this relationship breakdown is seen most in young people.

To evaluate

there has been study looking into gender difference and extra-marital affairs - it has been found that there was a significant trend in different reasons why each gender chose to cheat in a relationship. It was found that males would be much more likely to cheat due to a lack of stimulation, or lack of sex, while the woman would cheat due to lack of social skills - she wasn't being loved enough. With this information we can guess that these are generally the reasons for each gender why they chose to break up with the other.

Also looking at maintenance difficulties, we can suggest the idea of a long distance relationship being a problem not really being so much of a problem today. With the boom of technology and social media, it is a lot easier than it used to be to keep in contact with another person, with mediums such as skype or facetime. So this may not be such a significant reason anymore - Rohlfing stated from a student sample he found that at least 70 percent had tried to have a long distance relationship.

We can suggest that a form of a couples therapy can come after gaining insight on the reasons why - the therapy can help a couple by trying to improve the male’s ability to be affectionate with the female - while she has to realise that he won’t be as affectionate towards her.

Cultural differences also arise from explaining relationship breakdown to other places - Moghaddam states that relationship breakdown does not really occur in collectivist cultures - while the divorce rate in the UK is 50 percent, it's only less than 1 percent in collectivist cultures like India. This is because these cultures are based on arranged marriages which tie together families - a breakup of a couple is seen as a breakup of a family itself, and is seen as a critically negative life event for everyone around them.
5 Jun 2015, 03:11
Oliver Ward
Describe and evaluate two or more theories of the formation of romantic relationships 9+16


The first explanation of relationship breakdown is by Rollie and Duck - it states that there are separate stages of a relationship breakdown that people go through. They outline six stages - the first is breakdown - this is where one partner becomes dissatisfied - honeymoon period is over and arguments are starting to happen . The second stage is the intra-psychic stage - this is the stage where the partner begins to notice the other’s faults and only focus on them. They start to become emotionally withdrawn. What follows this is the dyadic stage. This stage sees the other partner become aware of this dissatisfaction - they are told about it or they figure out something is wrong. This part of the breakdown allows for restoration - the two can try and figure out a resolution and go back to normal, or the relationship ends. The next stage is social - where the breakup is made public and friends and family are used as an emotional crutch for help. The grave dressing phase follows this - this is where the two begin a new life. Stories are made up to be told to others, about the relationship and how the breakup went. Finally the resurrection phase sees the two be ready for a new relationship. They go out into the world with everything they’ve learned, using what they have learnt in the old relationship as guidance in the next one.

To evaluate

firstly we can comment that it doesn't particularly view the relationship breakdown in such a negative way - but that it allows an opportunity for personal growth, and gives them the chance to learn from their mistakes - a survey undertaken on undergraduate students and past relationships found that their past relationships eventually gave them lessons to be learnt which they could apply in the future relationships. While this backs up the point stated, we can note that this survey was taken on undergraduate students - these students tend to have a lot more short term relationships due to the large concentration of students at their university, making the sample unrepresentative to a whole population. It is unlikely a couple breaking up after 50 years will have much to say about positive personal growth.

We can also note that there are gender differences in personal growth - we can suggest that females would benefit from it more as they are more likely to discuss their emotions with their social circle then men are, who tend to bottle it in and not tlak about it.

this theory allow allows implication that the relationship can be saved at certain parts of the breakdown , and that it is not doomed as soon as a partner becomes unhappy. This has allowed the implication of couples therapy to be used which allow a couple to realise the stage of the breakdown they are in, giving them a chance to attempt to fix the problem with better insight.

Oliver Ward
Loudness compensation is a setting found on some hi-fi equipment and equalisers that increases the level of the high and low frequencies.[1] This is intended to be used at low listening levels, to compensate for the fact that as the volume of audio decreases, the ears lower sensitivity to extreme high and low frequencies may cause these signals to fall below threshold.[2] As a result audio material may seem to become 'thin' sounding at low volumes, losing bass and treble, the 'Loudness compensation' button (often just labelled 'Loudness' or 'Loud') is intended to rectify this situation. See the section on Loudness for a more detailed explanation of the ears' sensitivity to sound as a function of frequency.

Sam Well
I tested my 20g dried shroom, 24cc Solution. AWESOME is all i got to say I had one of the BEST trips ever. We started with 1cc each and started feeling the effects almost immediately. Within 10min we where having the full level 1 experience. We decided to take another CC, Took us to level 2.... Within 10 min. By this time it was hard to keep track of time. But we did 1 more CC and that was all we needed.

NO unpleasent side effects... No upset stomach, or dizziness... nothing negative. It was VERY euphoric, very clear. We were tripping hard, yet we could think very clearly. Couldn't always speak clearly but the thoughts were profound and clear. The visuals where awesome.... everything was so alive and beautiful. The moon was full... so that made for a magical evening.

The greatest thing about the extract was the control we had over the dosage. Each dosage was equal with magic content. Unlike when you eat the shrooms themselves where the magical content will be different from shroom to shroom. So, dosage isn't quite as accurate. I've split a bag of shrooms with a friend before and got off way more than he did... on the same shrooms. With the extract we both knew we were getting the same amount.

I've had tea, chocolate shrooms, cooked with magic.. even psychedelic coffee, and this is by far the best method of consumption. I will be testing how long the extract lasts in potency
